In this context, Hexan-2-one is mentioned as part of a formulation combined with benzaldehyde aimed at protecting dogs from infestation by the brown dog tick, R. sanguineus s. l. The study suggests that this formulation could enhance the effectiveness of anti-tick vaccines, thereby reducing tick infestations and the transmission of tick-borne diseases. The relationship is significant as it highlights the potential role of Hexan-2-one in pest management strategies.

In this context, Hexan-2-one is identified as one of the volatile organic compounds (VOCs) that contribute to the discrimination between leishmaniasis-infected and non-infected dogs. The study highlights the significance of various VOCs, including Hexan-2-one, in odor modifications associated with infections, suggesting that these changes may play a role in the survival strategies of parasites by attracting disease-transmitting vectors. Thus, Hexan-2-one is relevant in the context of leishmaniasis as a potential biomarker for infection status in dogs.
